
[1]vehemency

   VE'HEMENCY, n. [L. vehemens, from veho, to carry, that is, to rush or
   drive.]

   1. Violence; great force; properly, force derived from velocity; as the
   vehemence of wind. But it is applied to any kind of forcible action;
   as, to speak with vehemence.

   2. Violent ardor; great heat; animated fervor; as the vehemence of love
   or affection; the vehemence of anger or other passion.

   I tremble at his vehemence of temper.
